  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining the Foundation**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the core objective: setting up that React 18+ app with Vite and TypeScript. I\'m focusing on the folder structure, ESLint config (specifically, with airbnb), and pre-configured settings. Currently, I am analyzing different approaches to quickly bootstrap everything for the user to hit the ground running, and plan to get the structure just right.\n\n\n**Implementing the Architecture**\n\nI\'m now diving into component creation and configuration. I\'m focusing on creating the `MainLayout` component, setting up a skeleton for the Zustand store (`formStore.ts`), and establishing basic routing for `MainLayout`. I\'m building a `constants.ts` file, and making sure there are zero TypeScript or ESLint errors. I\'ll provide `package.json`, Vite, Tailwind configs and the `MainLayout.tsx` code. I\'m following specific constraints for the folder structure and dependencies (including `tailwindcss`, `react-hook-form`, `zod`, `zustand`, etc.).\n\n\n**Constructing the Pieces**\n\nI\'m now focused on the component implementations and configurations. I\'m building `MainLayout` using the Stitch UI HTML/Tailwind as a foundation, creating a skeleton `formStore.ts` using Zustand, and establishing basic routing to render `MainLayout`. I am creating a `constants.ts` file for placeholder data. I am working to ensure no TypeScript or ESLint errors are present. I\'m implementing a step-by-step plan that involves installing packages, creating directories, and crafting `package.json`, and `.eslintrc.cjs` or equivalent configurations.\n\n\n**Refining the Configuration**\n\nI\'m now installing and configuring ESLint, making the necessary adjustments for TypeScript compatibility. Specifically, I\'m setting up `.eslintrc.cjs` to align with the airbnb style guide. Since I\'m using TypeScript, I\'m integrating the required TypeScript parser and plugin. I\'m also ensuring the correct plugin installations, like `eslint-plugin-import`, `eslint-plugin-react`, `eslint-plugin-react-hooks`, and `eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y`, to work properly with `eslint-config-airbnb`. Also, I\'m installing all the necessary eslint plugins.\n\n\n**Defining the Architecture**\n\nI\'m now focusing on dependency installation and the structure of `MainLayout.tsx`. I\'ll strictly adhere to the provided list for packages, using `install_applet_package`, even if some may seem redundant, and setting up the linting configuration. Then I\'ll meticulously extract the structural elements (`header`, `nav`, `main`, `footer`) from the given HTML to compose `MainLayout.tsx`.\n\n\n**Translating the Elements**\n\nI\'m now converting the HTML into JSX format, focusing on the icon replacements. I\'ll change all instances of `class` to `className` and use objects for `style`. Material Symbols should be converted to Lucide icons. I have a list of Lucide icons that map to material symbols. I\'ll also close self-closing tags like `<img />`. Additionally, I will change `for=` to `htmlFor=` for improved JSX compatibility.\n\n\n**Clarifying the Structure**\n\nI\'m now refining the `MainLayout` component definition based on the HTML provided. It\'s clear that it should handle the header, navigation (side nav and/or stepper), and footer, while the main content area will render child components. The main content will contain the title, bento grid and form, and be rendered using `children` or the `<Outlet />` element from `react-router-dom`.\n\n\n**Integrating the State**\n\nI\'m now integrating the form state management using Zustand into `formStore.ts`, keeping the logic inside the layout for now. I\'ve defined a basic `FormState` interface with `currentStep` and a `setStep` function. I\'ve created the `useFormStore` hook with `currentStep` initialized to 1, and the `setStep` function updating the state. I\'ve also added basic constants for loan limits and file sizes.\n\n\n**Configuring the Routing**\n\nI\'m now implementing the routing setup. I\'m focusing on wrapping the `<MainLayout>` with `<BrowserRouter>` and configuring a basic route structure using `<Routes>` and `<Route>`. I have a placeholder for the form and the main layout. I\'ll integrate the routing into `MainLayout.tsx`, and I\'m ensuring all is working as expected. I\'m configuring the main route to render a placeholder.\n\n\n**Enforcing the Standards**\n\nI\'m now focusing on enforcing strict ESLint rules, aiming for zero warnings. I\'m setting rules to `\"error\"` where applicable, and utilizing the `lint` script. I will also change the code to remove the \"Identity Verification\" form out into a separate component.\n\n\n\n**Refining the Layout**\n\nI\'m now integrating the mobile stepper into the `MainLayout` structure. I\'ll replace the Bento Grid form section with the `<Outlet />` component, which will allow rendering child routes inside the main content area. The `<MainLayout>` component will strictly use the provided design for structure, and I\'ll make sure it is accurate.\n\nI\'m now moving on to extracting the `extend` values and making changes to `vite.config.ts`, `tailwind.config.js` or `index.css`.\n\n\n**Adapting the Styles**\n\nI\'m now adapting the Tailwind configuration to utilize CSS variables for styling, focusing on `src/index.css`. I\'m taking the HTML Tailwind values and creating CSS variables for colors, radii, spacing, and fonts, using the `@theme` directive. This includes defining variables like `--color-on-primary-fixed-variant` and `--radius-DEFAULT`. I plan to integrate them properly.\n\n\n\n**Implementing the Colors**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided color palette by defining CSS variables in `src/index.css`. I\'m assigning each hex code to a corresponding variable, such as `--color-secondary-container: #7bf8a1;`. Now I\'m ensuring everything is set up correctly.\n\n\n\n**Applying the CSS Variables**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided CSS variable values into `src/index.css` to manage the styling. I\'m focusing on defining variables for all the values, including colors, radii, spacing, and fonts, to ensure consistency.\n\n\n**Defining the CSS Implementation**\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating font and text size variables defined in the HTML into the `src/index.css` file using CSS variables. I\'ll translate the specified font families (\"Inter\", \"Manrope\") and text sizes (e.g., `--text-body-sm: 14px;`) into CSS variables. I\'ll make sure they align with the provided UI seamlessly.\n\n\n**Establishing the Environment**\n\nI\'m now focusing on setting up the development dependencies and project directory structure. I\'m carefully compiling a list of dev dependencies, including `cypress`, `vitest`, `eslint`, and Airbnb-related plugins. I am also preparing the directory structure, which involves using `create_file` to create all the necessary folders for project components. I\'m focusing on ensuring everything is set up to align with the provided guidelines.\n\n\\n\\n\n\nI\'m translating the ESLint configuration, recognizing the need to use `.eslintrc.cjs` and setting `\"ESLINT_USE_FLAT_CONFIG=false\"` to maintain compatibility with the Airbnb style guide in ESLint 9. This configuration ensures that Airbnb\'s rules are applied correctly without causing any errors. I\'m finalizing this for optimal linting.\n\n\n**Resolving the Configuration**\n\nI\'m now dealing with the ESLint configuration, considering Vite 6 possibly using a flat configuration. To bypass this, I\'ll use `.eslintrc.cjs` and the `ESLINT_USE_FLAT_CONFIG=false` flag. The goal is to ensure smooth integration with the Airbnb style guide. I\'ll need to install `eslint@^8.57.0` to avoid potential peer dependency issues with `eslint-config-airbnb`.\n\n\n**Enforcing the Standards**\n\nI\'m now refining the ESLint configuration further to be stricter, and will ensure it throws errors on violations. I\'ve updated the settings to enforce all accessibility rules and ensure there are no warnings. I am preparing to install dependencies, and setting up the linter, making sure that it runs and verifies there are zero errors. Also, I am preparing the list of dependencies and devDependencies, using the exact provided package names.\n\n\n**Constructing the Layout**\n\nI\'m now starting on `MainLayout.tsx`, translating the design pixel-perfectly using the provided Tailwind classes. I\'m focusing on incorporating `Outlet` for child routes and the Lucide icons. I have a rough skeleton in place, and am making sure all HTML elements are correctly formatted into JSX, including the header and side navigation. I\'ll include the `<Outlet />` element from `react-router-dom` in its correct spot.\n\n\n**Translating the Header**\n\nI\'m now translating the HTML for the header section of `MainLayout.tsx` into JSX, with the focus on incorporating Tailwind classes and Lucide icons. I\'m converting the inline SVG to a Lucide icon and meticulously mapping the corresponding classes to ensure pixel-perfect rendering, and updating it for JSX compliance. I\'ll make sure the layout classes remain consistent.\n\n\n**Implementing the Buttons**\n\nI\'m now focusing on implementing the button components within the `header` element of `MainLayout.tsx`. I\'m replacing the `<Bell>`, `<HelpCircle>` and `<User>` Material Symbols with corresponding Lucide icons, and ensuring the provided Tailwind classes are correctly applied. I\'m also implementing the hover and active states using Tailwind classes and making sure there are no errors.\n\n\n**Refining the Navigation**\n\nI\'m now implementing the navigation structure within `MainLayout.tsx`, focusing on rendering the desktop and mobile versions. I\'m leveraging `NavLink` from `react-router-dom` to handle the routing and active states. I am using the provided CSS classes, and also extracting data from HTML to create navigation items for the desktop and mobile versions. I am making sure the layout remains unchanged.\n\n\n**Refining the Implementation**\n\nI\'m now integrating navigation items into the side navigation menu using `NavLink` components from `react-router-dom` within the `MainLayout.tsx`. I\'m replacing placeholder buttons with `NavLink` components. The focus is to map each HTML list item to the corresponding JSX, and to apply the necessary Tailwind classes, making sure all items function correctly.\n\n\n**Implementing the Menu**\n\nI am now translating the HTML for navigation items to functional JSX within `MainLayout.tsx`. I am focusing on replacing the `<button>` elements with `NavLink` components from `react-router-dom`, integrating them with Lucide icons, and ensuring correct styling and routing. The goal is a pixel-perfect rendering, with active states handled by `NavLink`, replacing Material Symbols with Lucide equivalents, ensuring the Tailwind classes are applied accurately.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Navigation**\n\nI\'m now completing the navigation component implementation within `MainLayout.tsx`. I\'ve translated the navigation items to `<NavLink>` components and incorporated Lucide icons, ensuring accurate styling and routing. The layout is pixel-perfect now, with active states working as intended, and all HTML converted to JSX. I\'m focusing on accuracy.\n\n\n**Integrating the Actions**\n\nI\'m now integrating the final submission button and the \"Save for later\" functionality within the navigation. I\'ll translate the existing HTML structure into JSX, ensuring proper styling and functionality. I will also incorporate Lucide icons, including the `<Send />` and `<Save />` icons, applying appropriate Tailwind classes for visual consistency.\n\n\n**Implementing the Stepper**\n\nI\'m now implementing the stepper within the navigation of `MainLayout.tsx`, focusing on rendering the step indicators dynamically. I\'m focusing on creating step indicator components for the \"Identity,\" \"Income,\" and \"Details\" steps and rendering these using appropriate conditional rendering and Tailwind classes. I\'m making sure it aligns with the updated mock.\n\n\n**Constructing the Footer**\n\nI\'m now focused on implementing the footer section within `MainLayout.tsx`, translating the provided HTML into JSX and integrating the \"Back\" button and the \"Next\" button. I\'ll translate the existing HTML structure into JSX, ensuring that styling and functionality are correct. I\'ll integrate the Lucide icon for the \"Back\" button, and apply the appropriate Tailwind classes for consistent appearance, ensuring responsiveness for both mobile and desktop.\n\n\n**Clarifying the Structure**\n\nI\'m now contemplating the placement of the form. I\'m considering whether the form elements should be directly within the `MainLayout` or extracted as child components, potentially rendered via `<Outlet />`. While the prompt suggests a direct implementation within `MainLayout`, I\'m evaluating the benefits of a more modular approach to enhance maintainability and reduce potential complexity. I\'ll make a decision based on best practices and the prompt\'s specifications.\n\n\n**Revising the Form Placement**\n\nI\'m revisiting the decision of form component placement, and now I understand the architecture should accommodate the form steps with `<Outlet />`. I\'ll create a `IdentityVerificationPlaceholder` and render it using the `<Outlet />` element from `react-router-dom` in `MainLayout.tsx`, because of the directions. I\'ll include the placeholder with basic text. This approach ensures modularity and adheres to the prompt\'s instruction of not implementing the form logic, just the form\'s structure, and the overall design.\n\n\n**Executing the Structure**\n\nI\'m now generating all required files using `create_file` and adapting existing ones with `edit_file`. I\'m integrating the Tailwind `@theme` directives and defining CSS variables for color, fonts, and spacing in `src/index.css`. This also involves including font imports. My attention is now on implementing the tool calls to generate the project file